hands_on_practices.problem:
A flat, symmetric and balanced laminate has the stacking sequence $\left[0/90/\pm 45\right]_{s}$ about its mid-plane. Each lamina is orthotropic under plane stress with reduced stiffnesses in the material axes $(1,2)$ given by $Q_{11}=145~\text{GPa}$, $Q_{22}=10~\text{GPa}$, $Q_{12}=5~\text{GPa}$, and $Q_{66}=7~\text{GPa}$. The thickness of each lamina is $t_{p}=0.125~\text{mm}$, and all eight laminae have the same thickness. Angles are measured in degrees with respect to the laminate $x$-axis.

Using Classical Lamination Theory (CLT), and starting from the definitions of the reduced stiffness in the material axes and its tensorial transformation to the laminate axes $(x,y)$, compute the laminate extensional stiffness matrix $[A]$ in the $(x,y)$ axes for this $\left[0/90/\pm 45\right]_{s}$ laminate. Then, by comparing the resulting $[A]$ to the general form required by in-plane isotropy under plane stress, determine whether the laminate is quasi-isotropic in the extensional sense.

To report a single numerical result, define the dimensionless quasi-isotropy defect measure
$$
J \equiv \sqrt{
\left(\frac{A_{11}-A_{22}}{A_{11}}\right)^{2}
+
\left(\frac{A_{16}}{A_{11}}\right)^{2}
+
\left(\frac{A_{26}}{A_{11}}\right)^{2}
+
\left(\frac{2A_{66}-\left(A_{11}-A_{12}\right)}{A_{11}}\right)^{2}
}.
$$
A laminate that is quasi-isotropic in extension has $J=0$. Compute $J$ for this laminate. Round your answer to four significant figures and express it as a pure number (dimensionless).
